sell_model_liquidity_sweep.summary: Complete sell model using equal lows as liquidity target. Equal lows form (accumulation), price sweeps those lows (manipulation), returns to sell zone, displacement creates OB+FVG (distribution). Focus on FVG over OB - algorithm returns to the void (imbalance), just needs 50% to continue.
key_points: Equal lows are NOT support - they are LIQUIDITY
2-3 candles at same area = liquidity pool - functional not technical
Sweep is fluid/destined, not violent - 20-30 pips that knocks people out
Sweep can be whole candle, not just wick
Displacement = structure shift WITH SPEED during sessions/Judas swings
FVG more important than OB - algorithm returning to the void
50% of FVG imbalance is key level
They don't teach this - this is what makes the difference
sequence: 2. Equal lows form (2-3 candles same area)
4. Price SWEEPS the lows - fluid destined movement

fvg_vs_ob.reason: Algorithm trying to bring price back to the VOID to balance
fvg_vs_ob.entry_level: 50% of the imbalance - TOUCH only, no candle close needed
fvg_vs_ob.why_touch_only: It's an algorithm. This is numbers. This is math. Price has to balance - when there's imbalance, price returns there to continue forward.
fvg_vs_ob.ashton_quote: That's why the displacement and fair value gaps are so darn important and they're really the key to all this.

chart_annotation_standards.topic: How to Properly Annotate ICT Charts
chart_annotation_standards.summary: Be SPECIFIC and SURGICAL. Use thin lines and small boxes on exact levels/candles. Tell the story - show the sequence of how patterns connect. Don't use vague circles or mark random patterns.
key_points: Thin horizontal lines for levels (equal highs/lows)
Small rectangles for OBs - fit the exact candle
Tight vertical boxes for FVGs - the actual gap
Labels RIGHT NEXT to what you mark
Show the STORY - how patterns connect
Don't mark sweeps without showing WHAT was swept
